      <text>
            <body>
                  <div type="essay">
                        <head><bibl><author type="writer"><ref target="people.html#MoodyElizabeth"
                                                  ><name>Elizabeth Moody</name></ref></author><title
                                          type="main" level="a"/><title> Art. 52. <hi
                                                rendition="#italics">Monument du Costume Physique
                                                &amp; Moral de la Fin du dix huitieme Siécle; ou,
                                                Tableaux de la Vie.</hi> Small 8vo. 2 Vols. pp: 360
                                          in all. 6s. Boards. Dilly. 1790.<lb/> Art. 53. <hi
                                                rendition="#italics">Pictures of Life</hi>: or, a
                                          Record of Manners, Physical and Moral, on the Close of the
                                          Eighteenth Century. Translated from the French. Small 8vo.
                                          2 Vols. pp: 440, in all. 6s. Boards. Dilly. 1790.<hi
                                                rendition="sup"><note><hi rendition="#italics"
                                                  ><title>Monthly Review</title></hi>, second
                                                  series, vol. 4, January 1791, pages 106-107.
                                                  Benjamin Nangle identifies <ref
                                                  target="people.html#MoodyElizabeth"
                                                  ><name>Elizabeth Moody</name></ref> as the author
                                                  of this review from an editor's marked copy of <hi
                                                  rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                                  target="people.html#ReviewMonthly">The Monthly
                                                  Review</ref></title></hi>. See Nangle, <hi
                                                  rendition="#italics"><title>The Montly Review,
                                                  Second Series, 1790-1815: Indexes of Contributors
                                                  and Articles</title></hi>, Clarendon Press, 1955.
                                                  This edition of this review article was edited by
                                                  Mary A. Waters with transcription, encoding, and
                                                  editorial assistance by Dillon Cullinan. The book
                                                  comprises 26 illustrations by the artists Sigmund
                                                  Freudenberger (1745-1801) and Jean-Michel Moreau
                                                  (1741-1814) with text by Nicolas Edme Restif de La
                                                  Bretonne (1734-1806), a writer of novels, short
                                                  stories, legal and philosophical essays,
                                                  historiography, autobiography, and even
                                                  pornography.</note></hi></title></bibl></head>
                        <p>The author of these descriptions sets out with promising to exhibit
                              pictures of the modes of thinking, and manners of acting, <hi
                                    rendition="#italics">peculiar</hi> to the present age: this led
                              us to expect some novelty in the subjects of these <hi
                                    rendition="#italics">paintings</hi>; of course we were a little
                              disappointed to meet with none but <hi rendition="#italics">old
                                    pictures</hi>: the same dissipation, the same <hi
                                    rendition="#italics">frivolité</hi>, and disposition to
                              gallantry, and the same general profligacy among the great, are here
                              represented as they have been so often described in past ages: nor can
                              we perceive any <hi rendition="#italics">peculiar</hi> excellence in
                              this painter's performances: his <hi rendition="#italics">colours</hi>
                              are often coarse: he has not taken a good likeness of Nature, either
                              in her moral or physical character; and she is mostly drawn in <hi
                                    rendition="#italics">unbecoming dresses</hi>. In a picture of
                              her in her physical capacity, we are presented with an <hi
                                    rendition="#italics">accouchement</hi><hi rendition="sup"
                                          ><note>Birth of a baby.</note></hi>. This is a favourite
                              subject with the artist, and he <pb n="107"/>paints it <hi
                                    rendition="#italics">con amore</hi><hi rendition="sup"
                                          ><note>Tenderly; lovingly.</note></hi> The companion to it
                              is a mother surrounded with <hi rendition="#italics">one-and-twenty
                                    children</hi>, a <hi rendition="#italics">groupe</hi> that not a
                              little enhances our admiration of <hi rendition="#italics">French
                                    population:</hi> nor can we contemplate this Galtic Hecuba<hi
                                    rendition="sup"><note>Wife of King Priam of Troy. They had 19
                                          children together.</note></hi> without some degree of
                              respect. Among the best of the pictures, is a gambling party, where
                              the fatal consequences of that pernicious vice are affectingly
                              pourtrayed. A melancholy story, displaying some of the cruel effects
                              of the present commotions in France, concludes the <hi
                                    rendition="#italics">exhibition</hi>.</p>
                        <p>The translator is a faithful copyist: but the <hi rendition="#italics"
                                    >colouring</hi> to which we object, in some of the <hi
                                    rendition="#italics">original</hi> pictures, is still coarser in
                              the <hi rendition="#italics">copies</hi>—This is not the fault of the
                              translator, but of the languages.</p>
                  </div>
            </body>
